# The Engineering Workflow — canonical reference

**Scope.** This is the single source of truth for how work moves in this repo: issue → branch →
worktree → implementation → commit → PR → gates → landing → close-out. It absorbs the CLAUDE.md
dev-flow block, the ADR-0024 orchestrator playbook, and the review-tier policy. CLAUDE.md carries
only a ~10-line operating card pointing here. Platform-specific tracker mechanics stay in
`references/pm/<platform>.md` (today: `linear.md`). Decision lineage: ADR-0023 (trimmed GitHub
Flow), ADR-0024 (parallel orchestration), ADR-0025 (mechanical gates + this consolidation,
SAD-175).

## §1 Charter

- `{{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}` is **always deployable** and **PR-only** — every change lands as the squash
  commit of a merged PR, `<PR title> (#N)`, one atomic commit per {{ISSUE_KEY}} issue.
- Every gate that can be mechanical **is** mechanical (Claude hooks, pre-push, land-pr.sh,
  main-guard); what stays convention is listed in §6.
- One {{ISSUE_KEY}} issue → one branch → one worktree → one owning agent. Never two agents in one
  working dir.

## §2 The loop (per issue)

1. **Pick up** — fire Radar (background) to set the {{ISSUE_KEY}} issue **In Progress** (step 0,
   the easy-to-forget one).
2. **Branch** — from the fresh default branch (`git.defaultBranch` in
   workflow.config.json), named with the tracker's generated `gitBranchName`
   so the PR auto-links.
3. **Worktree** — one per issue (§8); copy in the gitignored per-machine files
   (`git.copyIntoWorktree` in workflow.config.json).
4. **Implement** — cite R-IDs in code comments/tests; new field-discovered behavior goes to
   `docs/requirements.md`, not code comments.
5. **Commit** — **Hubert** commits on the branch (atomic, `<type>: <subject>` ≤70 chars, cites
   {{ISSUE_KEY}}-N; NO `Fixes` line — the PR body carries it). **Gotcha:** background Hubert can
   stall after staging while notifying "completed" — verify `git log` shows the SHA; if stalled,
   SendMessage-resume with "finish the commit".
6. **Push + PR** — the owning agent pushes and opens the PR (`Fixes {{ISSUE_KEY}}-N` in the body);
   fire Radar (background) → **In Review**.
7. **Gates** — CI + tiered review (§5); reviewers post SHA-pinned verdict comments.
8. **Land** — `/land <PR#>` → `tools/dev/land-pr.sh` (§6). Never raw `gh pr merge` (F1-blocked).
9. **Close out** — the 4 surfaces (§7) + remove the worktree.

## §3 Stations

| Station | Agent | Does | Never does |
|---|---|---|---|
| PM / board | **Radar** | issue state, relationships, filing, audits — background, never gates the build | code, builds, commits |
| Commits | **Hubert** | staging, atomic commits, history curation, secret scan | push, PR, merge, destructive ops without explicit authorization |
| Review | **Watson** | five-axis code review → APPROVE / REQUEST_CHANGES + marker comment | deep security audits, tests, fixes |
| Security | **Barb** | vulnerability audit → CLEARED / BLOCKED + marker comment | general quality review, fixes |
| Tests | **Pepper** | on-demand test authoring (Prove-It) — **not a standing gate** | production code, commits |
| Acceptance | **Negev** | browser-based end-to-end verification (browser surfaces only) | non-UI verification |

**Device discipline:** never run two device-touching stations (Pepper connectedAndroidTest, Negev
probing, install/verify flows) concurrently against one serial.

## §4 Orchestrator playbook (parallel work — ADR-0024)

- **The main agent orchestrates, does not implement.** Each eligible issue → its own
  branch/worktree → one `general-purpose` implementation agent owning it end-to-end
  (code · commit · push · PR · CI).
- **Eligibility gate:** independent · well-specified · low-ambiguity · unblocked · not
  fidelity-verification-bound. Ineligible work stays serialized with Jason.
- **Partition by file ownership** so parallel PRs can't collide; sequence dependent merges by
  `blockedBy` chains; **pre-assign** shared scarce resources (R-ID numbers, Room migration
  versions) before fan-out.
- **Two-tier verification:** emulator pool for FUNCTIONAL checks (each agent pinned to its own
  `-s <serial>`); the single physical device for FIDELITY/perf (gestures, IME, scroll/ANR).
- **The 4 adb rules:** (1) always `-s <serial>` (hook-enforced, D5); (2) per-agent host output
  paths; (3) never `adb kill-server`/`start-server` in a pool (hook-enforced, D4); (4) one
  shared adb daemon serves everyone.
- **Escalate, don't guess** — open questions go to Jason; don't fan out ambiguity.

## §5 Review gates + tiers

**Tier resolution** (file patterns live in `.claude/workflow.config.json` — single source; the
lists below are the semantics, not a second copy):

- **security** — if ANY changed file matches `review.securityTierPatterns` (workflows, gradle,
  manifests, network/feedback code, and the self-protection set: `.claude/settings.json`,
  `.claude/hooks/**`, `.githooks/**`, `tools/dev/land-pr.sh`, `tools/dev/setup-repo.sh`,
  `.mcp.json` — changing the gates requires Barb).
- **docs** — only if ALL changed files match `review.docsTierPatterns` (`*.md`, `docs/**`,
  `design/**`, `tasks/**`, `.gitignore`, the PR template, `acceptance-evidence/**`).
- **code** — everything else.

**Gate per tier:** docs = CI alone · code = CI + Watson · security = CI + Watson + Barb.

**Verdict-comment convention** (what land-pr.sh reads): one PR issue-comment per verdict —
line 1 is the machine marker, then a human-readable summary:

```
<!-- watson-verdict: APPROVE sha=<full 40-char headRefOid> -->     (or REQUEST_CHANGES)
<!-- barb-verdict: CLEARED sha=<full 40-char headRefOid> -->       (or BLOCKED)
```

**SHA pinning:** any push voids prior verdicts — land-pr.sh trusts only the **last marker per
agent** matching the **exact current head**. **Delta-review:** for a trivial follow-up push,
the reviewer reviews the delta and re-posts a fresh marker for the new sha ("delta review:
<what changed>; verdict unchanged").

## §6 Landing

The ONLY merge path is **`tools/dev/land-pr.sh <PR#>`** (via `/land`). Gates: G0 prereqs →
G1 PR open/not-draft → G2 CI required check SUCCESS → G3 tier →
G4 verdict markers @ head → G5 {{ISSUE_KEY}}-linkage (warn) → G6 squash-merge with explicit
`--subject "<title> (#N)"` → G7 API-verified landed subject + `git fetch --prune` →
G8 close-out checklist. `--dry-run` stops after G5 with a PASS/FAIL table.

**Enforcement map** — what stops a bypass at each layer:

| Layer | Binds | Mechanism |
|---|---|---|
| Claude hooks (committed `.claude/settings.json`) | every agent Bash call, all sessions/worktrees | D-rows (destructive ops) + F-rows (branch flow): F1 raw `gh pr merge`, F2 push-to-{{DEFAULT_BRANCH}} (token-wise), F3 bare push on {{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}, F4 history-writing git on {{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}, F5 {{DEFAULT_BRANCH}} deletion |
| `.githooks/pre-push` (via `core.hooksPath`) | any local push, any terminal | rejects updates to `refs/heads/{{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}` |
| `land-pr.sh` | the merge itself | gates G0–G7 run before the merge; its internal `gh pr merge` is invisible to the hooks (the funnel trick) |
| `main-guard.yml` | server-side, after the fact | every commit pushed to {{DEFAULT_BRANCH}} must be the squash commit of a merged PR — red run = a bypass happened |

**What stays convention (not mechanical):** verdict comments are agent-authored (spoofable in
principle — the G8 audit URLs are the $0 mitigation); human `gh pr merge` from a terminal is
ungated; Jason's own shells; **worktree isolation** (§2's "never two agents in one working dir")
— the F-rows guard `{{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}` only, so nothing stops a feature-branch checkout or
commit in the shared primary checkout, which can silently retarget a concurrent session's next
commit onto your branch (SAD-298; real near-miss 2026-07-14). Mitigated by convention only: keep
the primary on `{{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}` (reference-only) and take a worktree per issue (§8),
overriding any session default that says to work in place. An F6 hook row would make it
mechanical — open decision on SAD-298. **Escape hatches are Jason-only, ambient-env-only** —
`SKIP_BASH_SAFETY` / `ALLOW_DESTRUCTIVE` / `ALLOW_MAIN_PUSH` / `ADB_NO_SERIAL_OK`; an inline
`VAR=1 cmd` is blocked outright (D0) and wouldn't work anyway (hooks read their own env).

**False-positive remediation:** the hook scans embedded text too (heredocs, quoted strings,
commit messages). If a legitimate command trips a rule — e.g. authoring a doc that *mentions*
`git push origin {{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}`, or a commit message quoting a hatch assignment — author
the content with the **Write/Edit tools** (or `git commit -F <file>`), or reword; never bypass.

## §7 Close-out — the 4 surfaces

On every landing, walk exactly these four (≤2 min):

1. **Linear** — fire Radar (background) to verify the {{ISSUE_KEY}} issue reached **Done** (the
   GitHub integration usually drives it off `Fixes {{ISSUE_KEY}}-N`; Radar's pass is idempotent
   verification).
2. **R-ID** — update `docs/requirements.md` **iff** the change moved a quality bar or added
   field-discovered behavior (append-only; ⛔ Retire, never renumber).
3. **Todo snapshot** — refresh the affected line in `tasks/todo.md` (≤30-line snapshot) +
   bump "Last refreshed".
4. **ADR / spec-row** — **iff** architectural: ADR in `docs/decisions/` first, then a row in
   the spec-amendments table atop the project spec (`docs/specs/`).

**Explicitly retired surfaces** (do NOT maintain): plan.md checkbox ticking (frozen — Linear
tracks open work), the todo.md prose changelog (moved to `docs/history/`), PR-template
checkboxes (deleted — land-pr.sh checks the gates), duplicate CLAUDE.md edits (CLAUDE.md is a
card pointing here).

## §8 Worktree runbook

- **Add:** `git worktree add -b <gitBranchName> <git.worktreeRoot>/<issue-slug> {{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}`
  (`git.worktreeRoot` from workflow.config.json; or the session-native worktree tool). **One
  agent per worktree.**
- **Copy in** the gitignored per-machine files or the build dies early (Gradle: at
  `processDebugGoogleServices`): e.g. `local.properties`, `app/google-services.json`, and
  optionally `.claude/settings.local.json` (permissions allowlist → fewer prompts). List lives
  in `git.copyIntoWorktree`.
- The committed `.claude/settings.json` + hooks materialize automatically — safety wiring needs
  no copy-in.
- **Remove after landing:** `git worktree remove <path>` (+ delete the local branch; the remote
  branch auto-deletes on merge).
- Never bare `git stash` — worktrees share the stash stack with every other session.

## §9 Config

Machine-readable knobs live in **`.claude/workflow.config.json`** (SAD-181): tracker
coordinates, default branch, merge method, required-check name, tier patterns, verdict markers,
station agents (a `null` station disables its gate with a loud WARN), worktree copy-ins, doc
paths. `land-pr.sh`, `pre-bash-safety.sh`, and `lint-on-edit.sh` read it with hardcoded
fallbacks + WARN when absent. New machine? Run `tools/dev/setup-repo.sh` and follow its
PASS/FAIL table.
